</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Dual-energy computed tomography (CT) relies on material-dependent x-ray absorption behavior from concurrently acquired high– and low–kilovolt peak data and has a range of imaging applications. This article focuses on use of dual-energy CT in assessment of bowel disease. After a summary of relevant dual-energy CT image acquisition and postprocessing principles, the authors describe dual-energy techniques of greatest utility in evaluation of benign and malignant pathologic conditions in the bowel, including neoplastic, vascular, infectious, and inflammatory disorders, as well as in assessment of abdominopelvic trauma. The dual-energy postprocessing techniques of iodine-selective imaging and virtual monochromatic imaging have the broadest applicability in bowel imaging. They may be used for improved visualization of subtle differences in bowel wall enhancement or for quantitative assessment of altered enhancement for evaluation of a neoplasm or bowel ischemia. Iodine images and virtual monochromatic low–kiloelectron volt images are particularly helpful for assessment of a neoplasm, ischemia, infection, or inflammation, while iodine maps paired with virtual nonenhanced images are most helpful to differentiate iodine from other dense materials, as in gastrointestinal bleeding or trauma. In most applications, radiation doses at dual-energy CT are comparable to those at traditional CT. However, dual-energy CT may allow reduction in radiation dose by using virtual nonenhanced images that obviate an additional nonenhanced CT acquisition. Limitations of dual-energy CT are discussed, including potential challenges in acquisition, postprocessing, and interpretation.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2016</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150151">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150151">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig1a.jpeg" height="666" width="895" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Creation of iodine-selective images by dual-energy CT postprocessing. <b>(a)</b> Axial mixed CT image combines low– and high–kilovolt peak data to simulate a typical single-energy image and shows low-attenuation wall thickening in the gastric antrum and pylorus (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial virtual nonenhanced CT image was created by subtraction of the calculated iodine content. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine map image displays the iodine content in color. <b>(d)</b> Axial iodine overlay image superimposes the color iodine map on the gray-scale virtual nonenhanced image. A dual-energy region of interest in the thickened gastric wall (blue circle) shows no iodine content in comparison to an adjacent small bowel loop (yellow circle) with attenuation of 78 HU and calculated iodine density of 1.5 mg/mL. The gastric wall finding is consistent with edema from presumed gastritis rather than an underlying mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig1b.jpeg" height="666" width="880" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Creation of iodine-selective images by dual-energy CT postprocessing. <b>(a)</b> Axial mixed CT image combines low– and high–kilovolt peak data to simulate a typical single-energy image and shows low-attenuation wall thickening in the gastric antrum and pylorus (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial virtual nonenhanced CT image was created by subtraction of the calculated iodine content. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine map image displays the iodine content in color. <b>(d)</b> Axial iodine overlay image superimposes the color iodine map on the gray-scale virtual nonenhanced image. A dual-energy region of interest in the thickened gastric wall (blue circle) shows no iodine content in comparison to an adjacent small bowel loop (yellow circle) with attenuation of 78 HU and calculated iodine density of 1.5 mg/mL. The gastric wall finding is consistent with edema from presumed gastritis rather than an underlying mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig1c.jpeg" height="665" width="888" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Creation of iodine-selective images by dual-energy CT postprocessing. <b>(a)</b> Axial mixed CT image combines low– and high–kilovolt peak data to simulate a typical single-energy image and shows low-attenuation wall thickening in the gastric antrum and pylorus (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial virtual nonenhanced CT image was created by subtraction of the calculated iodine content. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine map image displays the iodine content in color. <b>(d)</b> Axial iodine overlay image superimposes the color iodine map on the gray-scale virtual nonenhanced image. A dual-energy region of interest in the thickened gastric wall (blue circle) shows no iodine content in comparison to an adjacent small bowel loop (yellow circle) with attenuation of 78 HU and calculated iodine density of 1.5 mg/mL. The gastric wall finding is consistent with edema from presumed gastritis rather than an underlying mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig1d.jpeg" height="665" width="887" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. Creation of iodine-selective images by dual-energy CT postprocessing. <b>(a)</b> Axial mixed CT image combines low– and high–kilovolt peak data to simulate a typical single-energy image and shows low-attenuation wall thickening in the gastric antrum and pylorus (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial virtual nonenhanced CT image was created by subtraction of the calculated iodine content. <b>(c)</b> Axial iodine map image displays the iodine content in color. <b>(d)</b> Axial iodine overlay image superimposes the color iodine map on the gray-scale virtual nonenhanced image. A dual-energy region of interest in the thickened gastric wall (blue circle) shows no iodine content in comparison to an adjacent small bowel loop (yellow circle) with attenuation of 78 HU and calculated iodine density of 1.5 mg/mL. The gastric wall finding is consistent with edema from presumed gastritis rather than an underlying mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig2a.jpeg" height="1254" width="1672" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Qualitative and quantitative assessment of iodine content. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed CT image shows a bowel loop (blue arrow) within a closed-loop small bowel obstruction, with a normal adjacent small bowel loop (red arrow) indicated for comparison. <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image shows no visible iodine color in the thickened wall of the obstructed loop (compared to the color evident in the adjacent uninvolved bowel), indicating differential enhancement due to bowel ischemia. <b>(c)</b> Coronal dual-energy CT image with region of interest circled reports attenuation of 43 HU in the thickened bowel wall on the mixed image (green boxes), which is decomposed to 37 HU on the virtual nonenhanced (<i>VNC)</i> image (yellow boxes) and 6.3 HU due to iodine contrast medium (<i>CM</i>; upper red boxes). Iodine density (lower red box) is calculated to be 0.0 mg/mL within the obstructed loop, for a relative iodine enhancement of 3.4% compared with the reference region of interest in the adjacent uninvolved small bowel (dotted square). <b>(d)</b> Graph of virtual monochromatic Hounsfield unit curves (with Hounsfield units on y-axis and kiloelectron volts on x-axis) for the same region of interest locations as in <b>c</b> shows much greater enhancement in the normal bowel loop (green curve) compared with in the obstructed loop (orange curve), as evidenced by the more rapid increase in Hounsfield unit values of the green curve as the kiloelectron voltage decreases. <b>(e)</b> Coronal virtual monochromatic CT image at 50 keV accentuates the iodine content to depict differential enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig2b.jpeg" height="1254" width="1674" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Qualitative and quantitative assessment of iodine content. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed CT image shows a bowel loop (blue arrow) within a closed-loop small bowel obstruction, with a normal adjacent small bowel loop (red arrow) indicated for comparison. <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image shows no visible iodine color in the thickened wall of the obstructed loop (compared to the color evident in the adjacent uninvolved bowel), indicating differential enhancement due to bowel ischemia. <b>(c)</b> Coronal dual-energy CT image with region of interest circled reports attenuation of 43 HU in the thickened bowel wall on the mixed image (green boxes), which is decomposed to 37 HU on the virtual nonenhanced (<i>VNC)</i> image (yellow boxes) and 6.3 HU due to iodine contrast medium (<i>CM</i>; upper red boxes). Iodine density (lower red box) is calculated to be 0.0 mg/mL within the obstructed loop, for a relative iodine enhancement of 3.4% compared with the reference region of interest in the adjacent uninvolved small bowel (dotted square). <b>(d)</b> Graph of virtual monochromatic Hounsfield unit curves (with Hounsfield units on y-axis and kiloelectron volts on x-axis) for the same region of interest locations as in <b>c</b> shows much greater enhancement in the normal bowel loop (green curve) compared with in the obstructed loop (orange curve), as evidenced by the more rapid increase in Hounsfield unit values of the green curve as the kiloelectron voltage decreases. <b>(e)</b> Coronal virtual monochromatic CT image at 50 keV accentuates the iodine content to depict differential enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig2c.jpeg" height="1256" width="1676" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Qualitative and quantitative assessment of iodine content. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed CT image shows a bowel loop (blue arrow) within a closed-loop small bowel obstruction, with a normal adjacent small bowel loop (red arrow) indicated for comparison. <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image shows no visible iodine color in the thickened wall of the obstructed loop (compared to the color evident in the adjacent uninvolved bowel), indicating differential enhancement due to bowel ischemia. <b>(c)</b> Coronal dual-energy CT image with region of interest circled reports attenuation of 43 HU in the thickened bowel wall on the mixed image (green boxes), which is decomposed to 37 HU on the virtual nonenhanced (<i>VNC)</i> image (yellow boxes) and 6.3 HU due to iodine contrast medium (<i>CM</i>; upper red boxes). Iodine density (lower red box) is calculated to be 0.0 mg/mL within the obstructed loop, for a relative iodine enhancement of 3.4% compared with the reference region of interest in the adjacent uninvolved small bowel (dotted square). <b>(d)</b> Graph of virtual monochromatic Hounsfield unit curves (with Hounsfield units on y-axis and kiloelectron volts on x-axis) for the same region of interest locations as in <b>c</b> shows much greater enhancement in the normal bowel loop (green curve) compared with in the obstructed loop (orange curve), as evidenced by the more rapid increase in Hounsfield unit values of the green curve as the kiloelectron voltage decreases. <b>(e)</b> Coronal virtual monochromatic CT image at 50 keV accentuates the iodine content to depict differential enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig2d.jpeg" height="1281" width="1675" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span>. Qualitative and quantitative assessment of iodine content. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed CT image shows a bowel loop (blue arrow) within a closed-loop small bowel obstruction, with a normal adjacent small bowel loop (red arrow) indicated for comparison. <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image shows no visible iodine color in the thickened wall of the obstructed loop (compared to the color evident in the adjacent uninvolved bowel), indicating differential enhancement due to bowel ischemia. <b>(c)</b> Coronal dual-energy CT image with region of interest circled reports attenuation of 43 HU in the thickened bowel wall on the mixed image (green boxes), which is decomposed to 37 HU on the virtual nonenhanced (<i>VNC)</i> image (yellow boxes) and 6.3 HU due to iodine contrast medium (<i>CM</i>; upper red boxes). Iodine density (lower red box) is calculated to be 0.0 mg/mL within the obstructed loop, for a relative iodine enhancement of 3.4% compared with the reference region of interest in the adjacent uninvolved small bowel (dotted square). <b>(d)</b> Graph of virtual monochromatic Hounsfield unit curves (with Hounsfield units on y-axis and kiloelectron volts on x-axis) for the same region of interest locations as in <b>c</b> shows much greater enhancement in the normal bowel loop (green curve) compared with in the obstructed loop (orange curve), as evidenced by the more rapid increase in Hounsfield unit values of the green curve as the kiloelectron voltage decreases. <b>(e)</b> Coronal virtual monochromatic CT image at 50 keV accentuates the iodine content to depict differential enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig2e.jpeg" height="1200" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig2e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2e</span>. Qualitative and quantitative assessment of iodine content. <b>(a)</b> Coronal mixed CT image shows a bowel loop (blue arrow) within a closed-loop small bowel obstruction, with a normal adjacent small bowel loop (red arrow) indicated for comparison. <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image shows no visible iodine color in the thickened wall of the obstructed loop (compared to the color evident in the adjacent uninvolved bowel), indicating differential enhancement due to bowel ischemia. <b>(c)</b> Coronal dual-energy CT image with region of interest circled reports attenuation of 43 HU in the thickened bowel wall on the mixed image (green boxes), which is decomposed to 37 HU on the virtual nonenhanced (<i>VNC)</i> image (yellow boxes) and 6.3 HU due to iodine contrast medium (<i>CM</i>; upper red boxes). Iodine density (lower red box) is calculated to be 0.0 mg/mL within the obstructed loop, for a relative iodine enhancement of 3.4% compared with the reference region of interest in the adjacent uninvolved small bowel (dotted square). <b>(d)</b> Graph of virtual monochromatic Hounsfield unit curves (with Hounsfield units on y-axis and kiloelectron volts on x-axis) for the same region of interest locations as in <b>c</b> shows much greater enhancement in the normal bowel loop (green curve) compared with in the obstructed loop (orange curve), as evidenced by the more rapid increase in Hounsfield unit values of the green curve as the kiloelectron voltage decreases. <b>(e)</b> Coronal virtual monochromatic CT image at 50 keV accentuates the iodine content to depict differential enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig2e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig3a.jpeg" height="666" width="888" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Colon cancer. Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image <b>(a)</b> shows circumferential wall thickening of the descending colon, with uniform iodine enhancement well demonstrated in color on an axial iodine overlay image <b>(b)</b>. The findings are highly suspicious for a neoplasm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig3b.jpeg" height="666" width="888" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Colon cancer. Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image <b>(a)</b> shows circumferential wall thickening of the descending colon, with uniform iodine enhancement well demonstrated in color on an axial iodine overlay image <b>(b)</b>. The findings are highly suspicious for a neoplasm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig4a.jpeg" height="629" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Small bowel lymphoma in a patient with a known history of lymphoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows an enhancing nodule (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image shows small bowel obstruction, with improved conspicuity of the enhancing nodule at the transition point (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig4b.jpeg" height="629" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Small bowel lymphoma in a patient with a known history of lymphoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows an enhancing nodule (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image shows small bowel obstruction, with improved conspicuity of the enhancing nodule at the transition point (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig5a.jpeg" height="699" width="935" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Rectal cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows marked asymmetric rectal wall thickening (arrow) representative of rectal cancer. <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay image shows diffuse iodine content in the mass. Quantitative analysis showed an iodine content of 1.9 mg/mL in a region of interest in the mass (blue circle), compared with an iodine content of 0.3 mg/mL in a comparison portion of the ascending colon (yellow circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig5b.jpeg" height="699" width="939" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Rectal cancer. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows marked asymmetric rectal wall thickening (arrow) representative of rectal cancer. <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay image shows diffuse iodine content in the mass. Quantitative analysis showed an iodine content of 1.9 mg/mL in a region of interest in the mass (blue circle), compared with an iodine content of 0.3 mg/mL in a comparison portion of the ascending colon (yellow circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig6a.jpeg" height="627" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Acute lower gastrointestinal hemorrhage. Coronal contrast-enhanced portal venous phase CT image <b>(a)</b> shows hyperattenuating material (arrow) in the lumen of the distal transverse colon. The material persists on a coronal iodine overlay image <b>(b)</b> but disappears on a coronal nonenhanced virtual CT image <b>(c)</b>, confirming active hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig6b.jpeg" height="627" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Acute lower gastrointestinal hemorrhage. Coronal contrast-enhanced portal venous phase CT image <b>(a)</b> shows hyperattenuating material (arrow) in the lumen of the distal transverse colon. The material persists on a coronal iodine overlay image <b>(b)</b> but disappears on a coronal nonenhanced virtual CT image <b>(c)</b>, confirming active hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig6c.jpeg" height="599" width="801" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Acute lower gastrointestinal hemorrhage. Coronal contrast-enhanced portal venous phase CT image <b>(a)</b> shows hyperattenuating material (arrow) in the lumen of the distal transverse colon. The material persists on a coronal iodine overlay image <b>(b)</b> but disappears on a coronal nonenhanced virtual CT image <b>(c)</b>, confirming active hemorrhage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig7a.jpeg" height="668" width="902" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Ingested material in a patient with suspected gastrointestinal bleeding. Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image <b>(a)</b> shows hyperattenuating material (arrow) in a small bowel loop in the left mid abdomen. The material disappears on an axial iodine map <b>(b)</b> but persists on an axial virtual nonenhanced CT image <b>(c)</b>, confirming that the finding does not represent active extravasation of iodine. The material was found to represent ingested bismuth.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig7b.jpeg" height="698" width="928" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Ingested material in a patient with suspected gastrointestinal bleeding. Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image <b>(a)</b> shows hyperattenuating material (arrow) in a small bowel loop in the left mid abdomen. The material disappears on an axial iodine map <b>(b)</b> but persists on an axial virtual nonenhanced CT image <b>(c)</b>, confirming that the finding does not represent active extravasation of iodine. The material was found to represent ingested bismuth.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig7c.jpeg" height="698" width="948" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Ingested material in a patient with suspected gastrointestinal bleeding. Axial contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image <b>(a)</b> shows hyperattenuating material (arrow) in a small bowel loop in the left mid abdomen. The material disappears on an axial iodine map <b>(b)</b> but persists on an axial virtual nonenhanced CT image <b>(c)</b>, confirming that the finding does not represent active extravasation of iodine. The material was found to represent ingested bismuth.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig8a.jpeg" height="636" width="936" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Bowel ischemia. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows multiple thickened small bowel loops (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay map shows diminished iodine content (0.0 mg/mL) in the region of interest (yellow circle) in the thickened loops, compared with an iodine content of 1.1 mg/mL in the adjacent normal left midabdominal loops (blue circle). <b>(c)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a thrombus (arrow) within a branch of the superior mesenteric artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig8b.jpeg" height="636" width="935" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Bowel ischemia. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows multiple thickened small bowel loops (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay map shows diminished iodine content (0.0 mg/mL) in the region of interest (yellow circle) in the thickened loops, compared with an iodine content of 1.1 mg/mL in the adjacent normal left midabdominal loops (blue circle). <b>(c)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a thrombus (arrow) within a branch of the superior mesenteric artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig8c.jpeg" height="563" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Bowel ischemia. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows multiple thickened small bowel loops (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay map shows diminished iodine content (0.0 mg/mL) in the region of interest (yellow circle) in the thickened loops, compared with an iodine content of 1.1 mg/mL in the adjacent normal left midabdominal loops (blue circle). <b>(c)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a thrombus (arrow) within a branch of the superior mesenteric artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig9a.jpeg" height="789" width="664" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Perforated duodenitis. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows hyperemic duodenal wall thickening due to duodenitis (blue arrow), with a focal extraluminal collection (red arrow) and surrounding fat stranding caused by ulcer perforation. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal iodine overlay image shows increased iodine content in the duodenal wall and surrounding the focal perforation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig9b.jpeg" height="790" width="661" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Perforated duodenitis. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows hyperemic duodenal wall thickening due to duodenitis (blue arrow), with a focal extraluminal collection (red arrow) and surrounding fat stranding caused by ulcer perforation. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal iodine overlay image shows increased iodine content in the duodenal wall and surrounding the focal perforation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig10a.jpeg" height="703" width="939" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Enteritis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple thickened left-side small bowel loops and adjacent mesenteric stranding representing enteritis secondary to bile peritonitis after liver biopsy. <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay image improves detection of inflammatory hyperemia in the thickened bowel wall and mesentery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig10b.jpeg" height="703" width="936" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Enteritis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple thickened left-side small bowel loops and adjacent mesenteric stranding representing enteritis secondary to bile peritonitis after liver biopsy. <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay image improves detection of inflammatory hyperemia in the thickened bowel wall and mesentery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig11a.jpeg" height="703" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Acute appendicitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows a fluid-filled appendix with a hyperemic wall (arrow), a finding that represents acute appendicitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay image highlights iodine content in the hyperemic wall of the appendix (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig11b.jpeg" height="703" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Acute appendicitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows a fluid-filled appendix with a hyperemic wall (arrow), a finding that represents acute appendicitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay image highlights iodine content in the hyperemic wall of the appendix (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig12a.jpeg" height="666" width="894" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Diverticulitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows localized sigmoid colon wall thickening (arrow) with surrounding fat stranding and fascial thickening. <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay image shows iodine content in the thickened wall (arrow), as well as surrounding inflamed fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig12b.jpeg" height="666" width="882" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Diverticulitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows localized sigmoid colon wall thickening (arrow) with surrounding fat stranding and fascial thickening. <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay image shows iodine content in the thickened wall (arrow), as well as surrounding inflamed fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig13a.jpeg" height="702" width="641" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 13a</span>. <i>Clostridium difficile</i> colitis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows wall thickening throughout the colon, with enhancing mucosa and prominent vasa recta (arrows) representing <i>C difficile</i> pancolitis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image highlights increased enhancement in the mucosa and vasa recta (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig13b.jpeg" height="702" width="641" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 13b</span>. <i>Clostridium difficile</i> colitis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced mixed CT image shows wall thickening throughout the colon, with enhancing mucosa and prominent vasa recta (arrows) representing <i>C difficile</i> pancolitis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal iodine overlay image highlights increased enhancement in the mucosa and vasa recta (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig14a.jpeg" height="702" width="935" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 14a</span>. In a patient with ulcerative colitis, axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image <b>(a)</b> shows bowel wall thickening and mucosal enhancement (arrow), findings that are more conspicuous on an iodine overlay image <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig14b.jpeg" height="702" width="935" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 14b</span>. In a patient with ulcerative colitis, axial contrast-enhanced mixed CT image <b>(a)</b> shows bowel wall thickening and mucosal enhancement (arrow), findings that are more conspicuous on an iodine overlay image <b>(b)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig15a.jpeg" height="630" width="839" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Infected Hartmann pouch. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows marked wall thickening in an isolated Hartmann pouch that contains an air-fluid level (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay image shows iodine content in the wall, with a measurable iodine density of 1.6 mg/mL in the region of interest (red circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150151/asset/images/large/rg.2016150151.fig15b.jpeg" height="630" width="836" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Infected Hartmann pouch. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows marked wall thickening in an isolated Hartmann pouch that contains an air-fluid level (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial iodine overlay image shows iodine content in the wall, with a measurable iodine density of 1.6 mg/mL in the region of interest (red circle).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150151&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Johnson TR. Dual-energy CT: general principles. <em>AJR Am J Roentgenol</em> 2012;199(5 suppl):S3–S8.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.2214/AJR.12.9116">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23097165/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Dual-energy+CT%3A+general+principles&amp;author=TR+Johnson&amp;publication_year=2012&amp;journal=AJR+Am+J+Roentgenol&amp;pages=S3-S8&amp;doi=10.2214%2FAJR.12.9116&amp;pmid=23097165">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Toepker M, Moritz T, Krauss B, et al. Virtual non-contrast in second-generation, dual-energy computed tomography: reliability of attenuation values. <em>Eur J Radiol</em> 2012;81(3):e398–e405.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ejrad.2011.12.011">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22236702/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Virtual+non-contrast+in+second-generation%2C+dual-energy+computed+tomography%3A+reliability+of+attenuation+values&amp;author=M+Toepker&amp;author=T+Moritz&amp;author=B+Krauss&amp;publication_year=2012&amp;journal=Eur+J+Radiol&amp;pages=e398-e405&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.ejrad.2011.12.011&amp;pmid=22236702">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Zhao LQ, He W, Li JY, Chen JH, Wang KY, Tan L. Improving image quality in portal venography with spectral CT imaging. <em>Eur J Radiol</em> 2012;81(8):1677–1681.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ejrad.2011.02.063">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.